			<p>UCF community members who want to help Haitian earthquake victims can drop off much-needed items at several locations around campus through Friday, Jan. 29.</p>
<p>Student-led Volunteer UCF last week announced details about their drive, which will benefit Haitian relief efforts by the nonprofit Harvest Time International based in Sanford. The nonprofit has been stocking and sending items for survivors of last week&rsquo;s 7.0-magnitude earthquake that struck Port-au-Prince, Haiti.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m sure there are a lot of members of the UCF community who&rsquo;ve been directly affected by the crisis,&rdquo; Volunteer UCF student director Jessica Schwendeman told nearly 100 students from several organizations during a meeting Tuesday. &ldquo;All of us working together can make a bigger impact.&rdquo;</p>
<p>To see a list of donation items click <a href="http://www.vucf.getinvolveducf.com/haiti_donations.pdf">here</a>. Campus drop-off locations include the UCF Health Center, FAIRWINDS&nbsp;Alumni Center, Student Union -- both the Information Desk and Office of Student Involvement, on the second floor -- and Recreation and Wellness Center.</p>
<p>UCF's student-athletes collected money, hygiene and medical supplies and non-perishable food items prior to two basketball games last week. All collected resources and supplies will be donated into the relief effort through the Clean the World Foundation and Harvest Time International organizations.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s times like these where we see our true colors as UCF student-athletes,&rdquo; UCF&nbsp;Student-Athlete Advisory Commitee&nbsp;Vice President Emily Maynard said. &ldquo;Even though this horrific event took place in another country, we are trying to do whatever we can to help those in need ... We (student-athletes) are extremely lucky to have the opportunities we have here at UCF, and this is a chance to give back to those who are in desperate need of our help.&rdquo;</p>
<p>For the Volunteer UCF-led effort, volunteers were asked to help sort and pack supplies bound for Haiti on Saturday, Jan. 16. A second opportunity to sort and pack supplies on behalf of Harvest Time International will be held Saturday, Jan. 30, in two shifts from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.</p>
<p>More information for this event is posted on the <a href="http://www.vucf.getinvolveducf.com/">Volunteer UCF Web site</a>. Students, faculty and staff members and alumni are welcome to help in this &ldquo;universitywide service day,&rdquo; Schwendeman said.</p>
<p>&quot;The images of suffering and loss coming from Port-au-Prince are heartbreaking,&quot; said UCF President John Hitt. &quot;I urge all members of our generous UCF community to help the earthquake victims of Haiti. Our record of partnering with local, national, and international communities proves that we can make a difference and aid those desperately in need.&quot;</p>
<p>Other student organizations and faculty members continue collecting donations.</p>
<p>Club Kreyol is accepting canned goods, personal hygiene items and clothing donations at the Multicultural Student Center in UCF&rsquo;s Student Union and in donation boxes around campus. </p>
<p>Last week, the UCF's International Medical Outreach Chapter collected monetary donations outside the Student Union. </p>
<p>College of Education professors quickly collected medical supplies several days after the earthquake for a group of Haitian doctors and nurses who will travel to the island. Assistant Professor Edwidge Crevecoeur-Bryant, who was born in Port-au-Prince and still has family members in Haiti, organized the donation drive.</p>
<p><strong>Celebrating Haiti</strong></p>
<p>Efforts also are under way to organize charity events for Haiti. Among them, the UCF Campus Activities Board will host &ldquo;Operation Haiti Help Out&rdquo; from 8 to 11 p.m. Wednesday, Jan. 27, in the Pegasus Ballroom to collect donations and celebrate Haitian culture.</p>
<p>The group is looking for students, performers, poets and others who would like to be involved with the event. E-mail <a href="mailto:cab@mail.ucf.edu">cab@mail.ucf.edu</a> for more information.</p>
<p><strong>Candlelight Vigil</strong></p>
<p>UCF students pledged during a candlelight vigil Friday evening by the Reflecting Pond to &ldquo;support the full recovery of Haiti for the long term&rdquo; and vowed they would not let up.</p>
<p>The vigil, which also featured songs and prayers, was organized by the UCF student group Club Kreyol with support from several other student organizations. At the end of the vigil, students lit each other&rsquo;s candles while some of them sang the Haitian national anthem. Enough students attended the vigil to surround the entire Reflecting Pond.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The people of Haiti are living a nightmare,&rdquo; said speaker Jamal Kitnurse, a UCF student who also praised the Haitian community as strong, resilient and determined to not give up.</p>
<p>David Benoit, a UCF graduate student who lost a cousin in this week&rsquo;s earthquake, described the tragedy as a &ldquo;call to action&rdquo; for students and others to help.</p>
<p><strong>Dealing With Tragedy</strong></p>
<p>UCF&rsquo;s Counseling Center is available to help members of the university community with issues related to the earthquake, including how to deal with affected family members and how to cope with the devastation.</p>
<p>The center hosted a forum, &quot;Healing Your Hurt from the Haiti Earthquake,&rdquo; Tuesday evening in the Pegasus Ballroom of the Student Union.</p>
<p>For more information, call the Counseling Center at 407-823-2811.</p>
<p><strong>Help Beyond Campus</strong></p>
<p>UCF Board of Trustees member Harris Rosen announced last week that his longtime foundation, The Harris Rosen Foundation Inc., had joined forces with U.S. Sen. Bill Nelson&rsquo;s office and several local Haitian community leaders to help victims.</p>
<p>The foundation is currently accepting monetary donations and supplies &ndash; such as antibiotics, towels, bug spray, blankets and hygiene products, but no clothes &ndash; at various locations throughout the community.</p>
<p>The foundation has a connection to Haiti, having sent volunteers to the impoverished country in the past on health and educational outreach missions.</p>
<p>Drop-off locations currently include the Rosen Centre Hotel, 9840 International Drive; First Haitian Baptist Church, 4701 Lennox Blvd.; and Child Development Center of Orlando, 11553 Winter Garden Vineland Blvd.</p>
<p><strong>Students &lsquo;On the Ground&rsquo;</strong></p>
<p>Several UCF student groups recently spent time in Haiti on volunteer projects and are organizing relief efforts.</p>
<p>Among them is the UCF chapter of Engineers Without Borders, whose students last traveled to the island country in December to provide communities with more reliable sources of clean water.</p>
<p>A handful of students from UCF&rsquo;s International Medical Outreach organization spent six days in Haiti last year, treating hundreds of patients of all ages and conditions.</p>
<p><strong>Want to Help?</strong></p>
<p>UCF&rsquo;s News &amp; Information office will continue to list student and staff and faculty member projects in the coming days. If you have a project or volunteer effort you would like listed, please contact Christine Dellert at <a href="mailto:cdellert@mail.ucf.edu">cdellert@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Get Involved:</strong></p>
<p><a href="http://pegasus.cc.ucf.edu/~kreyol/"><strong>Club Kreyol</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.ewbucf.org/"><strong>Engineers Without Borders at UCF</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.vucf.getinvolveducf.com/"><strong>Volunteer UCF</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.cab.ucf.edu/"><strong>Campus Activities Board</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.rosenhotels.com/news_2010-01-14_harrisRosenReliefEffortHaiti.asp"><strong>Harris Rosen Foundation&nbsp;Inc.</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="http://imoucf.com/"><strong>International Medical Outreach at UCF</strong></a></p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 3rd largest in the nation with more than 53,500 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
